  "prompt": "Which is the best book of linear algebra?",
  "response": "Several linear algebra books are highly regarded, and the \"best\" can depend on your background and learning style. Here are some top recommendations:\n\n1. For Beginners\n- \"Linear Algebra and Its Applications\" by Gilbert Strang\n- Considered very accessible and practical\n- Excellent explanations and real-world applications\n\n2. Theoretical/Rigorous Approach\n- \"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler\n- More mathematically sophisticated\n- Focuses on proofs and abstract understanding\n\n3. Comprehensive Textbook\n- \"Linear Algebra\" by Serge Lang\n- Very mathematical and thorough\n- Good for advanced students and mathematicians\n\n4. Computational Approach\n- \"Linear Algebra\" by Jim Hefferon\n- Free online textbook\n- Good balance between theory and computation\n\n5. Problem-Solving\n- \"Linear Algebra Problem Book\" by Paul Halmos\n- Great for practicing and deepening understanding\n\n6. Engineering/Applied Focus\n- \"Linear Algebra and Learning from Data\" by Gilbert Strang\n- Modern approach with machine learning applications\n\nRecommendation depends on:\n- Your mathematical background\n- Purpose (theory, application, computation)\n- Personal learning style\n\nGilbert Strang's books are often considered the most beginner-friendly and practical.",
